summary.seg: MS Gg.1.1 is a Trilingual compendium of texts put together in the early fourteenth century. It contains literary, historical, grammatical, scientific, astronomical, theological, pastoral and devotional texts and is predominantly written in Anglo-Norman but also contains Middle English and Latin. As the French scholar Paul Meyer commented in 1886, 'Ce livre est à lui seul toute une bibliothèque'.
Featured in The moving word exhibition at Cambridge University Library.

msItem.author: Walter de Bibbesworth
msItem.title: Tretiz de langage
msItem.rubric: 279v Le tretiz ki munseignur Gauter de Bitheswey fistt a madame Dyonise de Mountechensi pur aprise de langage
msItem.incipit:
279v Femme ke aproche sun teins

msItem.note: This treatise in octosyllabic couplets, known also as "Aprise de franceis", "Femme", and Femina, is in effect a French vocabulary arranged by categories from the care of an infant through the possessions and occupations of a man of property. (Dean 1999, p. 160). It survives in two recensions. MS Gg.1.1 preserves the longer recension with prose prologue but lacks the letter which usually also precedes the text. Interlinear English glosses, provided by the author, accompany the text throughout.

msItem.author: Peter of Langtoft
msItem.title: Chronicle of England, Part 3: The Reign of Edward I
msItem.rubric: 328v Ici commence le Brut coment li bon rei Edward gaigna Escotz e Galis
msItem.incipit:
328v Ky volt oyr des reys coment chescune vesquist
En le ille de Brutus Bretainne appeller feist
msItem.explicit:
345v Wer never dogges there
Hurled out of herre
Fro coylthe ne cotte
msItem.note: Written in the late thirteenth and early fourteenth centuries, this chronicle in monorhymed alexandrine laisses, composed by Pierre de Langtoft, canon of Bridlington (Yorkshire), runs to more than 9000 lines, depending on the redaction. It is in three parts: the legendary history beginning with the arrival of Brutus; the reigns of Anglo-Saxon and Norman kings to the death of Henry III (1271); and the reign of Edward I during which Langtoft was living. (Dean 1999, p. 43). MS Gg.1.1 contains only the third part, preceded by a 26-line prologue which summarises the first two parts. The text breaks off with the bishops' consent to give the king aid in 1296, and closes with a 9-line song in English. (Dean and Boulton 1999, p. 44).
Seven lines in Latin are added at the foot of fol. 345v.

msItem.title: Le Brute d'Engletere abregé
msItem.rubric: 484v Ici commence le Brute d'Engletere abregé
msItem.incipit: 484v Scotez beati seignurs
msItem.note: This version of the text is extant in this manuscript alone. Zettl considered the work undoubtedly translated from some text of the short English metrical chronicle with which he printed it (p. xxxii); but Legge thought it more likely that a French octosyllabic poem was the source of both this prose and the English verse. (Dean 1999, p. 31).

msItem.title: Elegy for Edward I
msItem.incipit:
489r Seignurs oiez pur dieu le grant

msItem.note: This poem was composed after the coronation of Edward II (25 Feb. 1308). It is in ten octosyllabic huitains, rhyming ababbcbc, except in Stanza IX which has ababbaba. A rhymed couplet added to the first stanza was perhaps intended as a refrain, but there is no indication in the manuscript for its repetition. (Dean 1999, p. 58).

foliation.p: The manuscript was foliated 1-633 in ink on the upper right corner of each recto at some point after the missing folios were removed. Several leaves (113, 125, 164, 204, 244, 324, 345, 384, 392-399, 629-632) are foliated in the upper margin in a 16th-century hand qui semble avoir été exécutée avec négligence (Meyer 1886, p. 283).

collation.p:
The manuscript consists of 55 quires as follows:
Quire 1:8, wanting leaf 8 (fols 1-7)
Quires 2-21:12 (fols 8-247)
Quire 22:12, leaf 6 only stub remaining (fol. 252a) (fols 248-258)
Quires 23-30:12 (fols 259-354)
Quire 31:10 (fols 355-364)
Quires 32-35:12 (fols 265-412)
Quire 36:12, wanting leaves 1, 11 and 12 (fols 413-421)
Quire 37:12, wanting leaves 1 and 4 (fols 422-431)
Quire 38:12, wanting leaf 3 (fols 432-442)
Quires 39-42:12 (fols 443-490)
Quire 43:4 (fols 491-494)
Quires 44-53:12 (fols 495-614)
Quire 54:14 (fols 615-628)
Quire 55:6, leaf 6 only stub remaining (fol. iiir) (fols 629-633)

Bradshaw added pencil quire signatures (a-z, aa-tt, A-M) throughout the manuscript in the lower right corner of the first leaf of each quire and noted on adjacent leaves where leaves were missing. His collation, dated November 1860, is recorded on the modern paper endleaf.

layout.p: Ruled in crayon, most pages are written in 2 columns with 36-40 lines. Fols 261v-264v, 265v-279v, 328v-345v are written in a single column of 38-40 lines in verse; fols 407r-439v are written in 38 long lines as prose interspersed with illustrations. Fols 279v-294r are written double-spaced to leave room for an interlinear gloss.

handNote.p: Written by several scribes in Gothic bookhand (textualis).

Diagrams:
358v-362r, 374v-378v Diagrams of world including its antipodes, elements, moon, sun and their eclipses, seven planets and seven days of week, all illustrating L'image du monde.
490v Diagram of the human brain with five cells or ventriculi representing the five 'powers' of thought (the common or imaging sense, imagination, estimation, cogitation and memory), illustrating Qualiter caput hominis situatur.

Historiated initials:
8r Blue initial D in pink frame on gold ground with a clerk, presumably Ralph of Linham, and an open book (9 lines)
407r Rose initial S in blue frame on gold ground with St Paul holding a sword and book (11 lines)
510r Blue initial D with pink frame on gold ground with King Boctus and Sydrac the Philosopher (8 lines)

Ornamental and minor initials:
Blue or purple initials (2-10 lines) on purple or blue and gold ground, with white ornamentation and foliage scroll infill (occasional human or animal heads), at beginning of remaining books (6v, 17r, 21v, 24r, 36v, 46r, 75v, 96r, 111r, 113v, 120r, 122r, 135r, 139v, 261r, 264r, 265r, 265v, 272r, 279v, 294v, 328v, 346r, 347r, 390v, 392v, 393r, 394v, 397v, 399v, 403r, 404v, 440r, 464v, 466v, 469r, 470v, 472v, 474r, 476v, 479v, 484v, 490r, 491r, 495r, 505r, 627r, 628r, 629v).
Blue or red initials with red or blue penwork flourishing (2-7 lines) to chapters and subdivisions.

Border decoration:
Blue, purple and gold bars extending from historiated and larger ornamental initials to form partial borders supporting grotesques and animals and decorated with ivy and trefoil leaves in green, orange, and gold; sketches of birds (17r, 24r, 479v), rabbit (329r).

decoDesc.decoNote: Two illuminators worked on the manuscript; one was responsible for illuminating L'image du monde (346r-390r), the Apocalypse (407r-439v) and the diagram of the human brain (490v); the other for the decoration of the rest of the manuscript.

bindingDesc.p: Rebound in goatskin by Douglas Cockerell and Son, Grantchester, 1972.

history.origin: First half of 14th century, after 1307 C.E. England Basing their arguments primarily on dialectal features of the Middle English texts, Thiolier proposes an origin in the West Midlands (Thiolier 1989) while McIntosh suggests a possible Irish provenance (McIntosh et al. 1986).

provenance.p: A note on fol. i(v) in a seventeenth-century hand reads: 'Bought of Mr Washington'. Washington is well-known as a London bookseller of the seventeeenth century (cf. Watson 1966, p. 29).

The manuscript was owned by John Moore (1646-1714) Moore, John, 1646-1714 , Bishop of Ely. Bishop Moore's collection was donated to the University Library by King George I (1660-1727) George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 in 1715.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on unpublished MS notes by M. R. James and the description prepared for Western Illuminated Manuscripts: A Catalogue of the Collection in Cambridge University Library by Paul Binski and Patrick Zutshi, with the collaboration of Stella Panayotova, Cambridge, 2011 (used here by kind permission of Cambridge University Press).

availability.p: Entry to read in the Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card for admissions procedures contact Cambridge University Library Admissions). Contact the Manuscripts Department for further information on the availability of this manuscript
